&lt;h3 id=&#34;other-features&#34;&gt;Other features
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;the feature &amp;ldquo;conversions&amp;rdquo; contains a function of conversion between Satoshi and Bitcoin, and a function to convert the timestamp.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;the feature &amp;ldquo;merkle_tree&amp;rdquo; contains the functions useful to rebuild the Merkle&amp;rsquo;s root and to display the all tree.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;the feature &amp;ldquo;recherche&amp;rdquo; (search) offer multiples functions of searching : a function who look for the biggest amount of BTC transfert inside the file, one that can get the same research but for the block, another one that can calculate the volum of exchange of a day.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;the module &amp;ldquo;tris&amp;rdquo; (organize) allows us to organize in O(n log n) every block depending of the timestamp it&amp;rsquo;s got. Let&amp;rsquo;s remind that when we download blocks from the blockchain, it happens that some blocks are not in the chronological order.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Finally, the feature &amp;ldquo;Calculs&amp;rdquo; contains the functions that allows us to extract the public keys, their hashes, and their adresses.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;multithreading&#34;&gt;Multithreading
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;After our first use of our parsor, this one was really slow. Generating the Merkle&amp;rsquo;s tree was also really slow. We made some optimization with the help of threads inside lecture_frac and the merkle_tree.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The idea here was that one thread work on a certains amount of blocks. For that, we need to know the number of block inside the file and their size. A block begins with the magic bytes, followed by the block&amp;rsquo;s size. So we need to read the first 8 bytes and to move the cursor. We stock this inside a vector. Then, we need to check that the number of threads is above the number of block, else there is no need to use the threads. It&amp;rsquo;s a simple operation : just divide the number of block per number of threads. If we use the threads, then we give the number of block it needs to work on and where to start on the buffer.&lt;/p&gt;
